# Cursor Rules — Shyre

> These rules are identical to `CLAUDE.md`. If you update one, update the other.
>
> Persona sync is stricter: every persona has three files (`docs/personas/<name>.md`, `.claude/agents/<name>.md`, `.cursor/rules/persona-<name>.mdc`) that must move together.

## Project

Stint is a time-tracking and invoicing app. Next.js 16 (App Router) + Supabase + Tailwind CSS 4. Deployed on Vercel.

## TypeScript — strict, no exceptions

- `strict: true` + `noUncheckedIndexedAccess`. Never loosen.
- No `any` — use `unknown` and narrow, or define a proper type.
- No `@ts-ignore`, `@ts-expect-error`, or `eslint-disable`.
- No non-null assertions (`!`) unless guarded in the same scope.
- Explicit return types on exported functions and server actions.
- Handle all error cases — no swallowed catches.
- Use `import type` for type-only imports.

## File organization

- Co-locate tests: `actions.test.ts` next to `actions.ts`
- Co-locate page components with routes: `clients/new-client-form.tsx`
- Shared components in `src/components/`, hooks in `src/hooks/`, types in `src/types/`

## Naming

- SQL columns: `snake_case`
- TypeScript: `camelCase` for variables/interfaces
- Components: `PascalCase`, filenames: `kebab-case`
- Server actions: `verbNounAction`

## Supabase

- Server Components: `createClient()` from `@/lib/supabase/server`
- Client Components: `createClient()` from `@/lib/supabase/client`
- Server Actions: always verify `auth.getUser()` first
- RLS handles authorization — never bypass it

## Testing (>90% coverage)

- Vitest for unit + integration, Playwright for E2E
- Every new file needs a test file — no exceptions
- Test behavior, not implementation. Cover error paths and edge cases.

## Security

- MFA support (TOTP) from day one
- No secrets in code — env vars only
- No string interpolation in queries — use parameterized methods
- Validate all user input in server actions
- GitHub tokens are secrets — never log or return in list queries

## Form & button rules (MANDATORY)

Every form:
- Submits on Enter (native `<form>` + submit button)
- Autofocuses the primary field on open
- Uses SubmitButton from @/components/SubmitButton for spinner + disabled state
- Disables Cancel during pending
- Shows serverError inline + FieldError below fields

Every button:
- Uses shared button classes from @/lib/form-styles
- Shows loading state for async actions
- Disabled buttons look disabled (not ambiguous)
- Never silently succeeds or fails

Destructive flows:
- HIDE the original trigger when confirmation form is shown
- Typed-name confirmation for irreversible actions
- Cancel always present

## Redundant visual encoding (MANDATORY)

Every meaningful UI element uses 2+ of: icon, text, color.
- Status: color + text (never color alone)
- Buttons: icon + text
- Errors/warnings/success: color + icon + text

## Keyboard shortcuts (MANDATORY)

- Every primary action has a shortcut with visible `<kbd>` badge
- `/` focuses search, `N` = new item, `Cmd+S` = save, `Escape` = cancel
- `Space` = start/stop timer (when no input focused)

## i18n (MANDATORY)

- `next-intl` — every user-facing string uses `t("key")`
- Locales: `en`, `es` in `src/lib/i18n/locales/{locale}/{namespace}.json`
- Server: `getTranslations()`, Client: `useTranslations()`
- No hardcoded text in components

## Overlays

- Default: inline expansion (1-3 fields)
- Dropdown panel: forms needing more space
- Modal: destructive confirmations or complex multi-step only
- All overlays dismissible via Escape. No nested modals.

## Navigation feedback (MANDATORY)

- Every in-app navigation must give visible feedback within 100ms.
- `<TopProgressBar />` is mounted in the root layout; it fires on any in-app `<a>` click and snaps to complete on pathname change. Don't roll a per-page bar.
- `<LinkPendingSpinner />` (uses `useLinkStatus` from `next/link`) goes inside every navigation `<Link>`'s children — sidebar items, dashboard cards, doc index links. Per-link spinner so users see *which* link they hit.
- Add a `loading.tsx` next to any `page.tsx` whose server render does non-trivial work. Keep skeletons simple — TopProgressBar already signals "loading"; loading.tsx just keeps the layout from emptying.
- For non-link interactions (server actions, mutations), use `<SubmitButton>` per the form rules — not the progress bar.

## Documentation (MANDATORY)

- Docs live in `docs/` and are served in-app at `/docs` via react-markdown + remark-gfm.
- Structure: `docs/guides/features/` for cross-role feature docs (apply to everyone), `docs/guides/{agency,bookkeeper,admin}/` for role-specific additions only. `docs/reference/` for technical, `docs/security/` for audit log, `docs/personas/` for AI personas.
- The `/docs` landing is role-aware: surfaces relevant links based on logged-in user's role mix. Audience browse cards are secondary, not the hero.
- Every user-facing feature has a guide in `docs/guides/features/`, shipped in the same commit as the feature. Add a role-specific entry only if something is genuinely role-only.
- Required updates per change:
  - New feature → `docs/guides/features/<feature>.md` (+ role-specific only if needed)
  - Schema change → `docs/reference/database-schema.md`
  - New module / shell concept → `docs/reference/modules.md`
  - New env var → `.env.example` AND `docs/guides/admin/env-configuration.md`
  - Security change → `docs/security/SECURITY_AUDIT_LOG.md` (append-only)
  - Deferred / unshipped → noted in the relevant guide + `docs/personas/README.md`
- Guide format: title → where it lives → how-to steps → constraints / permissions → keyboard shortcuts → related links. ≤ ~200 lines; split if it grows.
- Don't duplicate content across guides. Write once; link from the others.
- Don't leave stale guides when features are removed. Delete or mark deprecated with a date.
- "Shipped but undocumented" is not shipped.

## Proactive development

- Fix issues immediately — no TODOs, no deferring
- Every feature: complete, tested, documented, localized
- Be proactive about improvements

## Personas (MANDATORY)

- Source of truth: `docs/personas/*.md` (8 personas). Tool wrappers at `.claude/agents/` and `.cursor/rules/persona-*.mdc` must reference the source, not duplicate it.
- Auto-engage alongside regular work when these patterns are touched:
  - `src/**/*.ts(x)` or `supabase/migrations/**` → QA Tester
  - `supabase/migrations/**`, `src/lib/supabase/**`, `src/lib/safe-action.ts`, `src/lib/system-admin.ts`, `src/lib/org-context.ts`, `**/actions.ts`, `src/app/auth/**` → Security Reviewer
  - `src/app/**/*.tsx`, `src/components/**/*.tsx` → UX Designer **and** Accessibility Auditor (separate passes)
  - `src/lib/modules/**`, `supabase/migrations/**`, new `(dashboard)/*/page.tsx` → Platform Architect
- Stakeholder voices (Solo Consultant, Agency Owner, Bookkeeper) are **manual invoke only** — engaging them on every change is noise.
- **Persona sync rule:** every persona has three files — `docs/personas/<name>.md`, `.claude/agents/<name>.md`, `.cursor/rules/persona-<name>.mdc`. Editing any one requires editing the other two in the same commit.
- Personas review, they don't implement. Each file ends with a concrete checklist, ≤100 lines.
- Personas are lenses, not gatekeepers — conflicting reviews are fine; the human decides.
- Prune checks that become lint rules / tests. Update personas when prod surprises slip past them.
